{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:25:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:25:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"716"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/716"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.14,0.09,0.06,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108847"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/716"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91211"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"1598"},{"type":"tags","id":"2934"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"9085"},{"type":"tags","id":"9086"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"9697"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1212"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28281"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108847"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-month history of malaise and weight loss of eight kilograms. Over the last four days his urine has become dark and his stools pale coloured. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. One week ago he returned from a two-month working holiday in Kenya where he took regular proguanil as malaria prophylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with visible jaundice. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft and non-tender with no organomegaly. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin 287 \u00b5mol/L (\u0026lt; 25)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlkaline phosphatase 1910 U/L (40-130)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGamma glutamyl transferase 799 U/L (\u0026lt; 50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine transaminase 321 U/L (\u0026lt; 51)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin 30 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the pancreas","Yellow fever","Falciparum malaria","Adverse drug reaction","Choledocholithiasis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of obstructive jaundice due to a mass in the head of the pancreas. The combination of significant weight loss, painless jaundice, and markedly elevated alkaline phosphatase in an older adult is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the pancreas\u003C/strong\u003E. The absence of pain does not exclude the diagnosis, as painless jaundice is a common presentation when the tumour is located in the head of the pancreas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYellow fever\u003C/strong\u003E can cause jaundice but typically presents with high fever, severe myalgia, and headache in the acute phase. The pattern of liver function tests would show a more hepatitic picture rather than the predominantly obstructive pattern seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFalciparum malaria\u003C/strong\u003E can cause jaundice through haemolysis and hepatitis, but would typically present with fever, rigors, and other systemic symptoms. The recent travel history makes this consideration relevant, but the pattern of obstructive jaundice and weight loss is not typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eadverse drug reaction\u003C/strong\u003E to proguanil would be unlikely to cause this degree of cholestasis. Drug-induced liver injury typically shows a hepatocellular or mixed pattern rather than the predominantly obstructive pattern seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholedocholithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause obstructive jaundice but would not typically cause significant weight loss. Biliary colic would usually be present, and the onset is typically more acute than the indolent course described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe marked elevation of alkaline phosphatase out of proportion to transaminases, along with conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia causing dark urine and pale stools, confirms an obstructive pattern. In a middle-aged or older adult with no history of gallstone disease, this pattern with significant weight loss should prompt urgent investigation for pancreatic cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Painless jaundice with weight loss in older adults strongly suggests pancreatic cancer until proven otherwise","Obstructive jaundice is characterised by dark urine, pale stools, and predominantly elevated alkaline phosphatase","Travel history and medications are important but should not distract from concerning features of malignancy"],"references":["Park W, Chawla A, O\u2019Reilly EM. Pancreatic Cancer: A Review. JAMA. 2021 Sep 7;326(9):851\u201362. Available from: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/2783817"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91211"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"716"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91211"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T19:22:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T19:22:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"716"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108847"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"